Homework 3: Forecasting and Interpretability¶

Introduction¶

Teaching is a job that is underappreciated many times for a lot of reasons (reasons that I won't go into much details) but I believe that one of the tasks that teachers/professors/tutors do that is the most underappreciated is the fact that they have to teach to multiple people that come from different backgrounds, different cultures, different learning system, different pace, different everything. And that they have to come up with a plan to make sure that the material they are required to teach is actually, well...teachable to the many people that are learning. With the advanced technology that the world has grown into, students and teachers have many resources to deliver these materials: Khan Academy, YouTube Videos, interactive platforms, etc. However, even with the great amount of resources that technology has given us, teaching and learning are still difficult jobs to perform.

So what can we, as computer scientist, do? To help students learn better, to help teachers teach better, we have to first look at what students are already good at so that we can determine how to help them in the next topic. Using ASSISTments 2009-2010 non-skiller builder dataset, we can predict a student's next performance whether they will get the question right or not based on the student's current performance. The results show us that our models can predict at around 80% accuracy and that attempt_count, hint_count, and used_hints are one of our most important features, that is, the number of attempts a student took to solve a problem, the number of hints they used, and if they used any hints or not out of the total they were offered.

Some features that can be useful are: assignment_id, user_id, problem_id, ms_first_respone, attempt_count, hint_count, and hint_total. The target feature will be correct since we are trying to find out whether they get it correct or not.

Now we can create additional features, we are going to create three:

  1. If the student attempted more than once on a specific problem by looking at the column 'attempt_count', then we will create a new column called 'more_than_once' which will store a 1 if the student attempted the problem more than once. Otherwise, it will store a 0 if they attempted 1 or 0.
  2. The second additional feature will store the total number of problems that student did for this set of data by looking at how many unique problem_ids are stored associated to that student.
  3. If a student used all the hints provided to them, then we will create a new column called 'used_hints' which will store a 1 if tthe student used all the hints (hint_count) out of the total hints they were given (hint_total). However, if they did not use it or if their hint_total is 0, then it will store a 0.
In [22]:
# 1. if attempt_count > 1,  create new column 'more_than_once' is 1
more_than_once = df['attempt_count'] > 1
once = df['attempt_count'] <= 1

df.loc[more_than_once, 'more_than_once_attempt'] = df.loc[more_than_once, 'attempt_count'].apply(lambda x: x > 1)
df.loc[once, 'more_than_once_attempt'] = df.loc[once, 'attempt_count'].apply(lambda x: x > 1)
df['more_than_once_attempt'] = df['more_than_once_attempt'].astype('int')

# 2. number of problems a student did
for i in df['user_id'].unique():
    unique_user = df['user_id'] == i
    problems = df[df['user_id'] == i].count()['problem_id']
    df.loc[unique_user, 'problems'] = problems
df['problems'] = df['problems'].astype('int')

# 3. used all hints
df['used_hints'] = np.where(df['hint_count'] == df['hint_total'], 1, 0)
df['used_hints'] = np.where(df['hint_count'] == 0, 0, 1)
df

III. Train Models¶

i. Linear Model¶

We are going to use GridSearchCV class to tune hyperparameters of scikit-learn's LogisticRegression() model:

In [27]:
# Create LogisticRegression() model
log_model = LogisticRegression()

# Apply GridSearchCV on model
log_search = GridSearchCV(log_model, {
    'C': np.logspace(-3,3,7),
    'tol':[0.0001, 0.1, 0.5, 0.999],
})

Then fit this into our validation_df created earlier

In [28]:
# Fit search with validation data
log_search.fit(validation_df[features], validation_df[target])
Out[28]:
GridSearchCV(estimator=LogisticRegression(),
             param_grid={'C': array([1.e-03, 1.e-02, 1.e-01, 1.e+00, 1.e+01, 1.e+02, 1.e+03]),

Now that it's done fitting the values, let's see what the best estimator is:

In [29]:
print(log_search.best_estimator_)

LogisticRegression(C=0.001)

Now we can use the model and fit values from the training_df, make the model predict using values from the testing_df, and calculate the accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 scores

In [30]:
# Fit model with training set
log_model.fit(training_df[features], training_df[target])

# Predict using testing set
log_predictions = log_model.predict(testing_df[features])

# Print prediction scores
print('Accuracy: ', round(accuracy_score(log_predictions, testing_df[target]), 3))
print('Precision: ', round(precision_score(log_predictions, testing_df[target]), 3))
print('Recall: ', round(recall_score(log_predictions, testing_df[target]), 3))

In [40]:
# Gradient Boosted Decision Tree ROC Curve

In [41]:

Now that we have all the values from the ROC curves for all the models created earlier, we can plot them using matplotlib package:

AUC for Linear model: 0.8153720153144253
AUC for Tree model: 0.8762599596511877
AUC for Neural Network: 0.8652774820480544

We get a three ROC curves for each of the models and they are all decent ROC curves. The least best performing model is the linear model. It is the closest one to the straight dotted line meaning it is good at predicting values but comparing with our other ROC curves, it is the least performing one with an AUC of approximately 0.82.

The next best performing model is the neural network with an AUC of approximately 0.86. And finally, followed by the best performing model, the GBC tree with an AUC of approximately 0.88. The ROC curves for the neural network and the GBC tree are very close together than the linear model. But all the ROC curves are at a decent distant away from the straight line.

V. Conclusion ¶

In conclusion, all of our models had an accuracy score prediction of around 80%. That means, that the chance that a student will get the next question right is about 80%. We can use this accuracy score to continue helping students and provide them resources on problems they are struggling with so that we can prepare them better for exams or state exams.

It is interesting to see that the most important features are attempt_count, hint_count, and used_hint because when you think of this problem in a non-computer scientist way or in a non-machine learning way (especially when you taken a couple of courses in Sociology), and you think what kind of features that are included in our dataset, that hints and attempts are important in determining a student's performance. Because if they used a hint or all the hints, it means that the student is not so familiar with the topic and needs more help to "master" the topic. The same thing can be said about the number of attempts.
